TY  - JOUR
T1  - Foresight and Public Utility Regulation
AU  - Gort, Michael
AU  - Wall, Richard A.
Y1  - 1988/02/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261530
DO  - 10.1086/261530
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 177
EP  - 188
VL  - 96
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The paper develops a model that shows the effects of rational expectations, and of efficient markets, on public utility regulation. It is shown that the feedback from investor expectations to regulatory behavior, together with investor expectations that take account of this feedback, basically alters the consequences of regulatory decisions. The analysis examines the effects of a deviation between the allowed rate of return and the cost of capital, with both perfect and imperfect investor foresight. It also assesses the consequences of differing expected growth rates. Conclusions are drawn for the effects of regulatory decisions on resource misallocation and of regulatory lag on incentives.
AB  - The paper develops a model that shows the effects of rational expectations, and of efficient markets, on public utility regulation. It is shown that the feedback from investor expectations to regulatory behavior, together with investor expectations that take account of this feedback, basically alters the consequences of regulatory decisions. The analysis examines the effects of a deviation between the allowed rate of return and the cost of capital, with both perfect and imperfect investor foresight. It also assesses the consequences of differing expected growth rates. Conclusions are drawn for the effects of regulatory decisions on resource misallocation and of regulatory lag on incentives.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261530
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261530
Y2  - 2024/03/22
